
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Working Abroad, Working with Others: How Firms Learn to Operate International Joint Ventures
AU  - Barkema, Harry G.
AU  - Shenkar, Oded
AU  - Vermeulen, Freek
AU  - Bell, John H. J.
Y1  - 1997/04/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256889
DO  - 10.5465/256889
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 426
EP  - 442
VL  - 40
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Successful international joint ventures entail both learning to operate across national boundaries and learning to cooperate. Hypotheses grounded in organizational learning theory were tested with event-history analysis and data on 1,493 expansions of 25 large Dutch firms between 1966 and 1994. Experience with domestic joint ventures and with international wholly owned subsidiaries contributed to the longevity of international joint ventures, but prior experience with international joint ventures did not.
AB  - Successful international joint ventures entail both learning to operate across national boundaries and learning to cooperate. Hypotheses grounded in organizational learning theory were tested with event-history analysis and data on 1,493 expansions of 25 large Dutch firms between 1966 and 1994. Experience with domestic joint ventures and with international wholly owned subsidiaries contributed to the longevity of international joint ventures, but prior experience with international joint ventures did not.
